replies.text:
@ThinkingandTinkering 
That’s a fair price. Thanks.
And…has anyone tried printing in a vacuum? Or would the workpiece not be able to solidify?

@ThinkingandTinkering 
Never mind. That’s just my brain after a 10 hour shift and I’m really starting to drift. 
But this turbine really has me turning in my sleep. I keep seeing the magnets on the outer perimeter of the wheel. But then it may not fly so much. Anyway, thank you for your perseverance!

@Robert Murray-Smith  it’s not about having a go, I really enjoy the work you do, but the data is almost dimensionless at this point, It would just be nice to have something tangible I could work with.

And I’m not gonna sit here and be an armchair expert either, how about I design you up a simple circuit that would be nothing more than a hand full of components and arduino. Most of which you would have lying around. Get it to sweep over the rpm range measuring voltage and current, whilst plotting it against rpm and torque using a cheap load cell mounted in a 3D printed base, and an optical rotation sensor.

At the press of a button it could spit out both the characteristic curve of both the generator and turbine independently from each other.

@ThinkingandTinkering What you are testing now is quite fascinating, and am looking forward to it's final form. 
Sorry, I should have said "In a DC motor or Generator", as I was talking about the volts measurement you were making from the Turbine.
Power measurements are even more important for lower speed turbines, as there is little to work with, and every Joule counts.

@ThinkingandTinkering Fair enough. Good point.

If it's a case of accessibility, I myself might have made an expanding foam and body filler former, and moulded a few out of fiberglass. Or used it as the neccecery excuse I'd need to build the vacuum forming machine I've always had a hankering to own. Then again, my brother trained as a coach builder, so he'd probably think hand forming them out of mild steel with a sandbag, mallet, blow torch, and some planishing slappers would be the only appropriate process (Give him his dues though, he'd probable be able to make them neat, quickly and accurate out of steel. I'd only feasibly hit two of those in fiberglass on a good day. :D).

We all favour the technical solutions we're most familiar with. :D
